    'from' => 'Randy Hollingsworth randyh@svpal.org',
    'body' => 'The news about GDW upset me so much I accidentally disengaged my lurker
cloaking device, so I might as well transmit my $.02 credit\'s worth.

I feel that the best way to assure Traveller\'s future would be to declare
what I am willing to shell out for, to wit:

I\'m willing to pay $50.00 US for a CD-ROM archive of the Traveller rules.
The CD could accompany a reissue of the TNE main book, or just about any
book since they are so darn cheap to manufacture.

The Adobe Acrobat format would be ideal as it is cross-platform, and
provides security features that protect the publishing interests of
whoever picks up the system. (I don\'t work for Adobe.) I believe you can
disable printing and copy/paste operations to protect the material.

Since the TNE rules have become a tad cumbersome to administer, and it
really, really looks like all the tables in the TNE books were done in
Microsoft Excel, I\'d like to see some excel utilities for ship
construction and etc. on the disc. Excel is also cross-platform and
offers security features that prevent editing the formulas and data.

I wouls also be delighted if all barriers were dropped by the new
publisher on the writing of shareware utilities by the gamers. This would
promote more play due to increased ease of use, and the synergy between
developers and the publisher could help rejuvenate sales.  "You mean the
CD has the rules, the charts, and utilities too? I\'ll take it!!"

Utility programs could be required to read data from the CD, ensuring that only
authorized owners of the game could run any software, and utility makers
could be required to allow the publication of their work non-exclusively
on future CD\'s. I feel this would respect all the publisher\'s rights and
permit a beehive of innovative activity, albeit a non-commercial beehive.

I think including a CD will also encourage Mr. Miller or whoever is
adding to the Imperium to produce more material than is economical to
print, since CD duplication is dirt cheap. Finding plenty of extra stuff
on the CD is good for the gamer\'s wallet and enriches the Traveller
universe with more ideas.

That\'s my ideal future for Traveller. I look forward to seeing everyone
else\'s and eagerly await the next chapter in the Traveller saga, which I
have followed since 1978...

Best regards,
Randy Hollingsworth
randyh@svpal.org
randy@raydream.com


