From: sjhumphr@athena.bournemouth.ac.uk. (steven J Humphrey)

Can you publish the following advert for TRC both on your website and list
server?

***START OF MESSAGE***

At present, I am setting up a multimedia project management company called
"TRC" (or Traveller Reformation Company) in association with another
company called WebTop Publico and Azinko Korp Unlimited here in
bournemouth.uk to investigate, set up and recruit the necessary staff to
undertake multimedia projects based on Traveller following the closing down
of GDW Games.

***TRC is investigating a project idea to put Traveller onto CD-ROM (as
"traveller:the compact disk" or t:cd) as an interactive multimedia
encyclopedia with conventional eGame componants, e.g flight simulation/3D
shoot\'em up games, heavy on Animated 3D Graphics and content. Traveller has
always had computers integral to the system, and it seems logical to
include modern computing systems into traveller as an integral part of the
game system, and digitising Traveller on CD and via the Internet also seems
logical.

The t:cd project is therefore centered around literally putting the
traveller game system, rules, library data, subsystems e.g craft design,
character generation etc, and campaign data onto one or a series of cds,
designing the application that handles the data stored, adding a couple of
conventional game systems e.g a DoomII style eGame to make it sell, and
finally, selling the finished product to the distributors.

The t:cd will include an application software program to instal onto the
player\'s own Computer system to store and produce custom data e.g House
rules and campaign details, in addition to t:cd\'s encyclopedic functiions
and features. Combine these two features (multimedia CD and application
software) with the internet to update and support t:cd and to post
user-designed modules - in a similar way to DoomII\'s wads - and I believe
the true next era of traveller gaming will be released onto the 40 million
and more internet aware public.

The commercial aspect of t:cd is that cd\'s sell for around 50 bucks each
but once the software and data have been produced, the profit margins are
very attractive, costing only a quid or two per cd to mass produce.
Distributors then take a slice, producers, advertisers and other "fingers"
each take their chunks but overall, still a profitable proposition.

***The first phase of this project is to acquire the publishing rights, or
a license to publish, Traveller online and on CD. The second and third
phases are to recruit the relevent staff and to produce a working Demo in
time for EuroCon96. Tight scheduling I know but feasible and attainable
providing the licensing deal goes through. Following EuroCon96, the project
teams will develop a working alpha version within 12 months and full
release within two years.

***If you want to help produce, finance or otherwise develop t:cd project
then eMail me with how you can help.

